##########################################################################

	How to visualize the results with gnuplot

###########################################################################

Once a simulation has been conducted and the results have been post-processed:


1. in the directroy <<sph-blitz/results/ResultsInProgress>> run the script show damping to visualize
    the decrease of amplitude with each period.
  
 The syntax to run the script
   is for example:
   <<./../../gnuplot/1DWave/showDamping.sh>> 
  script produces the following figures in the newly created folder <<Visualization>>

  - <<Damping.png/eps>> shows the evolution of the Amplitude over the period number
    
  - <<Period.png/eps>> shows the temporal evolution of the period Time.
    BE AWARE: the accuracy of the shown period time can never be superior to the output interval time of 
	      the underlying simulation!!!



2. if visualization of temporal evolution of v, p, rho or x of the current simulation is desired:

2a)FIGURE
  in the directroy <<sph-blitz/results/ResultsInProgress>> run the script <<showShapeChange.sh>> to visualize
    the change of shape after a certain number of periods (input argument is time stamp of simulation result data
      that shall be compared to initial shape...(for traveling wave: be sure it is multiple of periodical time T)
    for example
<<./../../gnuplot/1DWave/showShapeChange.sh 08673000>>
  

2b) MOVIE
  i) run (in <<sph-blitz/src/outdata>>) the shell script <<sph-blitz/scripts/dat2punto.sh>> and redirect its output into 
  a file called <<punto.dat>>:
  do all this by typing:
  <<./../../scripts/dat2punto.sh > punto.dat>>
      (this merges all the output data in the file punto.dat, which can then be read by gnuplot)

  ii) run scripts
  <<waveMovieVelocity.gp>> 
  <<waveMoviePressure.gp>>  
  <<waveMovieDensity.gp>>
  <<waveMoviePosition.gp>> 
  in a gnuplot shell in the folder <<sph-blitz/src/outdata>>
  that means: a) stay at <<sph-blitz/src/outdata>>
	      b) type <<gnuplot>>
	      c) type <<load '../../gnuplot/1DWave/waveMovieVelocity.gp'>> for velocity movie (others equivalent)
	      d) press <<n>> for next instant, press <<p>> for previous instant